WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.769 --> 00:00:03.310
JOSEPH SMARR: My
name's Joseph Smarr.

00:00:03.310 --> 00:00:05.730
I'm an engineer on the
Google Photos team.

00:00:05.730 --> 00:00:07.930
And I'm delighted to have
Atul Singh here with us

00:00:07.930 --> 00:00:11.730
to-- I can't resist saying a
little bit about his biography,

00:00:11.730 --> 00:00:14.820
because I think-- you
know that Dos Equis

00:00:14.820 --> 00:00:17.125
commercial for the most
interesting man in the world?

00:00:17.125 --> 00:00:19.250
Still, it's like a slightly
dated reference by now.

00:00:19.250 --> 00:00:21.989
But I think Atul might
be my candidate vote

00:00:21.989 --> 00:00:23.530
if I had to vote
for a real life most

00:00:23.530 --> 00:00:24.800
interesting man in the world.

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:26.520
And maybe you'll
see why in a second.

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:30.790
So he was born in Goa,
India, and quickly became

00:00:30.790 --> 00:00:33.830
somewhat infamous, I would
say, because as a teenager,

00:00:33.830 --> 00:00:36.180
he became very active in
protesting what he saw

00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:39.382
as the political corruption
in the Indian royal families,

00:00:39.382 --> 00:00:40.840
and Indian government
and so forth,

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:42.810
and developed
quite a reputation.

00:00:42.810 --> 00:00:45.730
He then went on to become an
officer in the Indian military,

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:49.410
and was in combat in Kashmir and
in several other active combat

00:00:49.410 --> 00:00:51.950
zones against Islamic
fundamentalists and so forth.

00:00:51.950 --> 00:00:53.940
Luckily, he seems
to have survived.

00:00:53.940 --> 00:00:56.600
He then became a deep scholar.

00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:59.350
He has advanced degrees from
Oxford, and the Wharton School,

00:00:59.350 --> 00:01:02.308
and other places,
and was for a while

00:01:02.308 --> 00:01:04.599
a corporate lawyer at one of
the most prestigious firms

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:07.520
in London, representing Goldman
Sachs and the London Olympics

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:08.810
and other sorts of places.

00:01:08.810 --> 00:01:12.070
But in 2010, he decided
to abandon all of that

00:01:12.070 --> 00:01:16.140
and start "Fair Observer,"
which is a sort of news magazine

00:01:16.140 --> 00:01:17.440
journalism outfit.

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:19.950
It's a nonprofit with
a very global focus.

00:01:19.950 --> 00:01:22.990
And for me, it's something
where I've learned more

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:26.122
and felt like I've gotten a sort
of more deep and unbiased look

00:01:26.122 --> 00:01:27.580
at what's going on
around the world

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:29.871
and a more integrated, global
approach to understanding

00:01:29.871 --> 00:01:32.350
the news than almost any other
publication I can think of.

00:01:32.350 --> 00:01:34.100
And I think that's
largely thanks to Atul.

00:01:34.100 --> 00:01:36.350
And he's actually
recruited sort of a network

00:01:36.350 --> 00:01:38.010
of journalists across
the world to help

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:39.590
contribute to "Fair Observer."

00:01:39.590 --> 00:01:41.540
And he also writes for
it himself, of course.

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:43.684
And beyond that, you can
go to fairobserver.com

00:01:43.684 --> 00:01:44.850
if you want to check it out.

00:01:44.850 --> 00:01:46.350
I would encourage
you to do that.

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:48.485
He's also written for
"Huffington Post" and "Al

00:01:48.485 --> 00:01:51.000
Jazeera," and other
places like that.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.270
And in addition to that, he
teaches political economy

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:59.690
at both Berkeley and at the
IIT, and travels back and forth.

00:01:59.690 --> 00:02:01.030
He's a poet.

00:02:01.030 --> 00:02:03.480
He was a former
Himalayan mountaineer.

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:06.170
He's written an
award-winning play.

00:02:06.170 --> 00:02:06.670
He speaks--

00:02:06.670 --> 00:02:07.329
ATUL SINGH: Not quite.

00:02:07.329 --> 00:02:07.808
[LAUGHING]

00:02:07.808 --> 00:02:09.910
JOSEPH SMARR: He speaks six
or seven different languages

00:02:09.910 --> 00:02:10.868
from what I understand.

00:02:10.868 --> 00:02:13.776
And anyway, the point being,
I think you get the idea.

00:02:13.776 --> 00:02:15.400
It's a pretty unique
set of background,

00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:20.230
and I think makes him-- oh,
sorry-- I think uniquely

00:02:20.230 --> 00:02:23.370
qualified to speak to--
there's a set of things going

00:02:23.370 --> 00:02:25.270
around the world right
now, obviously, that

00:02:25.270 --> 00:02:27.410
have us all kind of
confused and worried.

00:02:27.410 --> 00:02:30.520
And Atul's sort of integrative
approach to both understanding

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:32.020
the history and
context of what's

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:33.140
going on in each
of these countries,

00:02:33.140 --> 00:02:35.380
and also an ability to sort
of synthesize it together,

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:36.880
I think, is what
makes me so excited

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:39.050
for him to come and talk
to us about the global rise

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:39.650
of the far right.

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:41.130
So with that,
please, take it away.

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:41.796
Thank you, Atul.

00:02:41.796 --> 00:02:43.895
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:48.564
ATUL SINGH: Thank you,
Joseph, for your kind words.

00:02:51.170 --> 00:02:54.950
It's a real pleasure
and a privilege

00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:56.120
and an honor to be here.

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:59.080
Thank you so much
for coming over.

00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:01.830
Thank you, Joseph,
for hosting me.

00:03:01.830 --> 00:03:05.910
I have to thank my
team, first of all.

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:07.990
And they are folks
who have worked

00:03:07.990 --> 00:03:10.980
with me, trudged the lows.

00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:14.510
And we are hoping for the highs.

00:03:14.510 --> 00:03:19.080
We have a managing editor who's
written the book, "The Arab

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:20.725
Uprisings," and
he speaks Arabic.

00:03:20.725 --> 00:03:23.550
And we have a Deputy Managing
Editor who's Russian,

00:03:23.550 --> 00:03:25.680
and her name is
Anna Pivovarchuk.

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:31.590
So imagine an Arab, a Russian,
and an Indian heading a ship.

00:03:31.590 --> 00:03:33.180
And somehow, it manages to work.

00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:34.670
And that's "Fair Observer."

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:37.680
And we have 1,600 plus writers.

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:41.720
We're nearing to 1,700 writers
now from over 40 countries.

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:43.090
And the premise is very simple.

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:46.390
The premise is if I
speak, and I give you

00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:49.240
a point of view, that's
one point of view informed

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:52.760
by my experience, my
cultural background,

00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:56.950
my philosophical beliefs, and
my historical understanding.

00:03:56.950 --> 00:04:01.020
But if, let's say, I put
forth my point of view,

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:04.930
and Joseph did, and Shael did,
who's sitting in the first row,

00:04:04.930 --> 00:04:09.020
and Alexander did, who's sitting
in the back with a Sydney

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:14.070
t-shirt, and so
did others, then we

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:19.209
would get a better to a better
understanding of the world,

00:04:19.209 --> 00:04:21.399
because each of us
has blind sites.

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:25.830
And when we share ideas,
and we share our thoughts,

00:04:25.830 --> 00:04:29.970
and we somehow think
through things together,

00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:32.640
cutting across borders,
backgrounds, and beliefs,

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:35.670
we get a better
approximation of the truth.

00:04:35.670 --> 00:04:39.000
So, so much so for the
fundamental philosophical idea

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.570
behind "Fair Observer."

00:04:41.570 --> 00:04:44.130
I am told I should tell
everyone these days

00:04:44.130 --> 00:04:46.170
to like us on social media.

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:47.660
I always forget that.

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:50.930
So now, since I'm at Google,
I'm telling you all to like us

00:04:50.930 --> 00:04:54.820
on Google+, of course,
first, followed by Facebook

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:58.380
and Twitter, and sign
up for our newsletter.

00:04:58.380 --> 00:05:00.380
So now that I've done
the mandatory pitch

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:02.650
that my team would
be proud of, let's

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:07.490
get cracking into a
rather somber issue.

00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:09.720
And the somber issue
is, very frankly,

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:12.030
the global rise
of the far right.

00:05:12.030 --> 00:05:14.420
Now before we carry
on into examining

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:17.630
what is the far right, let's
understand what is the right.

00:05:17.630 --> 00:05:20.240
And I have a very advanced
piece of technology

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:21.890
in Google that helps me.

00:05:21.890 --> 00:05:22.780
It is this.

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:26.130
It was invented a while
ago, apparently in China.

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:30.300
And there's another thing called
this, which is pencil, right?

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:34.070
And I tend to write my things
like this, as you can see.

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:37.910
I have really adapted
to the 21st century.

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:42.820
But if you look at the
origins of the word the right,

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:46.310
it goes back to that wonderful
event, or not so wonderful

00:05:46.310 --> 00:05:48.200
event, depending on your
point of view, which

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:50.480
was the French Revolution.

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:53.220
And after the French
Revolution, those

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:56.440
who supported l'ancien
regime, the old regime,

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:58.870
sat on the right.

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:00.300
[FRENCH]

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:03.610
And those who basically wanted
revolution, and some of them

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:07.610
wanted heads to roll, and heads
did roll, sat on the left,

00:06:07.610 --> 00:06:09.410
[FRENCH].

00:06:09.410 --> 00:06:15.290
And those on the right believed
in hierarchy, tradition,

00:06:15.290 --> 00:06:18.930
clericalism, which is you
should go to mass every Sunday.

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:21.150
I doubt very many Googlers do.

00:06:21.150 --> 00:06:24.060
You're all sinners, right?

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:24.650
Or not all.

00:06:24.650 --> 00:06:28.230
Some of you are not sinners.

00:06:28.230 --> 00:06:36.420
But anyway, the people
who sat on the right

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:40.110
also believed that inequality
and social stratification

00:06:40.110 --> 00:06:43.700
were the natural order
of the universe, which

00:06:43.700 --> 00:06:46.020
as George Orwell
put memorably, "some

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:47.790
are more equal than others."

00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:52.140
So those who are clever and who
are engineers work at Google,

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:55.010
and those who have no skills
except rudimentary pencil

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:59.080
skills live like our
artists in a garret.

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:02.050
That's the natural
stratification of the universe.

00:07:02.050 --> 00:07:05.070
And I'm just a
modern manifestation.

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:07.680
And of course, those who
do other menial jobs are

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:11.500
further down in the pecking
order of the universe and get

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:12.860
paid accordingly.

00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:19.820
Now, that premise that
inequality is important changes

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:21.220
for the right over time.

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:23.430
Instead of becoming
something by birth,

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:28.560
it becomes something
by ability and effort.

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:32.910
Now, what is that fundamental
belief on the right?

00:07:32.910 --> 00:07:34.210
It is very simple.

00:07:34.210 --> 00:07:38.660
If you give everyone the same
outcome, no one will work.

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:40.240
And it won't be fair.

00:07:40.240 --> 00:07:42.770
So if Joseph works
100 hour weeks,

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:45.840
he deserves a fine
villa by the sea.

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:49.120
And if, let's say,
Shael is lazy,

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:51.800
he deserves to be
homeless and bum around.

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:54.160
And maybe if Joseph
is feeling charitable,

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:58.100
he can give Shael a piece of
bread, and maybe some gruel.

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:00.480
And then, Shael
can be Oliver Twist

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:02.820
and say, "Please, sir,
can I have some more?"

00:08:02.820 --> 00:08:06.390
But the premise of the
right is very simple.

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:14.930
It's that the competitive
free market is largely just,

00:08:14.930 --> 00:08:18.170
because people should
get what they deserve.

00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:21.210
The just desserts.

00:08:21.210 --> 00:08:25.970
Not desserts as in ice
cream, but just desserts.

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:29.840
And the competitive free market,
according to this belief,

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:31.450
is free.

00:08:31.450 --> 00:08:35.390
It is largely fair, and
it rewards ingenuity

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:38.330
and industriousness.

00:08:38.330 --> 00:08:42.510
So if you're innovative,
you come up with a new idea,

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:48.460
and you somehow make that idea
popular by working very hard,

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:52.960
you deserve greater rewards
than those who don't.

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:59.210
And in this premise-- sorry,
in this belief system,

00:08:59.210 --> 00:09:02.650
is another premise that
markets achieve better outcomes

00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:05.210
than governments, because
governments are top-down.

00:09:05.210 --> 00:09:06.720
Governments are authoritarian.

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:10.030
Governments don't have
those price signals.

00:09:10.030 --> 00:09:16.191
So trusting markets is more
efficient than trusting

00:09:16.191 --> 00:09:16.690
governments.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:19.450
And that brings us
to something else,

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:23.080
which I call the equity
efficiency paradox,

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:26.050
or if equity
efficiency paradigm.

00:09:26.050 --> 00:09:30.680
And that is in the era of
the modern left-- modern,

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:37.830
I would say, post-Second
World War-- and right

00:09:37.830 --> 00:09:40.370
is the fundamental
defining feature

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:42.350
for two sides of the
political divide.

00:09:42.350 --> 00:09:45.916
If you are the
Labor Party in 1945,

00:09:45.916 --> 00:09:47.290
and you've just
won the election,

00:09:47.290 --> 00:09:50.360
you believe in a
National Health Service,

00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:53.240
because you believe that
the inefficiency that

00:09:53.240 --> 00:09:56.620
will be inherent in the
National Health Service maybe

00:09:56.620 --> 00:09:58.500
the drop in
innovation that might

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:03.930
happen because of a bureaucracy,
is worth it for greater equity.

00:10:03.930 --> 00:10:07.160
Everyone deserves
health care as a right.

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:10.170
That is a premise that
the left all across Europe

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:11.910
operates from.

00:10:11.910 --> 00:10:15.470
Everyone deserves
schooling as a right.

00:10:15.470 --> 00:10:18.980
Everyone deserves certain
inalienable rights

00:10:18.980 --> 00:10:24.870
that are more than just liberty
of expression and belief.

00:10:24.870 --> 00:10:28.270
Now if you're on
the right, you say,

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:32.100
the equity efficiency paradigm
is getting a little too

00:10:32.100 --> 00:10:33.830
unbalanced.

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:36.220
Because what we
believe is in freedom,

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:38.390
and freedom includes
the freedom to fail,

00:10:38.390 --> 00:10:41.190
and freedom includes,
at its most extreme,

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:42.280
the freedom to die.

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:45.200
You just didn't make it in
the evolutionary struggle.

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:48.880
It's a Darwinian view.

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:52.260
But there is something to
be said for both sides.

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:55.110
Because when societies
tip over to the extreme,

00:10:55.110 --> 00:10:59.450
far to the extreme of any
side, they sort of meander

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:03.570
and lose something intangible.

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:05.570
It's that critical balance.

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:09.400
And that critical balance is
different for every society.

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:12.460
Now, so much so for
this distinction

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:13.900
between left and right.

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:18.020
Let us understand
what is the far right.

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:22.520
Now the far right takes ideas
of inequality and stratification

00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:24.990
to absurd levels.

00:11:24.990 --> 00:11:29.420
It bases them not just on
birth, which is basically

00:11:29.420 --> 00:11:32.750
class and heredity, not
just on outcomes, which

00:11:32.750 --> 00:11:34.390
is belief in the free market.

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:40.370
It bases them on these ideas
of nation, race, ethnicity,

00:11:40.370 --> 00:11:41.880
or even religion.

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:46.620
So the classic example
is Nazi Germany.

00:11:46.620 --> 00:11:48.240
And Nazi Germany,
lest we forget,

00:11:48.240 --> 00:11:52.620
was the National Socialist
German Workers' Party.

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:55.780
There was the word
socialist in it.

00:11:55.780 --> 00:11:56.860
Most people forget that.

00:11:56.860 --> 00:11:59.860
Most people think they were
just this far right group, which

00:11:59.860 --> 00:12:02.260
wanted complete
unfettered freedom,

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:05.610
and that included freedom to
kill the gypsies and the Jews.

00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:08.290
But it was a little
more complex than that.

00:12:08.290 --> 00:12:12.940
And that brings me
to a second point.

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:14.580
The first one that
I made was the far

00:12:14.580 --> 00:12:17.905
right is predicated on nation,
race, ethnicity, religion, et

00:12:17.905 --> 00:12:19.280
cetera.

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:21.920
The second one is
that the far right

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:24.650
tends to be a strange
amalgamation of the right

00:12:24.650 --> 00:12:29.130
and left, which is
often forgotten.

00:12:29.130 --> 00:12:33.150
In terms of identity,
it draws upon the right.

00:12:33.150 --> 00:12:35.110
It draws upon
something primeval.

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:38.830
It draws upon this idea that
the German people, [GERMAN],

00:12:38.830 --> 00:12:40.240
we are one people.

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:41.590
We are somehow special.

00:12:41.590 --> 00:12:43.241
We are superior.

00:12:43.241 --> 00:12:45.040
All right.

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:48.560
But the economics,
now that everyone

00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:52.210
is special, now that
everyone is superior,

00:12:52.210 --> 00:12:55.540
then suddenly turn left wing,
because if everyone belonging

00:12:55.540 --> 00:12:59.910
to a certain race is superior,
then no one should be starving.

00:12:59.910 --> 00:13:03.220
So you have Hitler Youth.

00:13:03.220 --> 00:13:06.220
You pack off all the
nice, blonde, tall people

00:13:06.220 --> 00:13:09.010
to exercise and spend
time in the countryside,

00:13:09.010 --> 00:13:10.550
and the Untermenschen
conveniently

00:13:10.550 --> 00:13:11.725
to concentration camps.

00:13:14.420 --> 00:13:18.560
But if you are from
the superior race,

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:20.330
then you function
collectively together.

00:13:20.330 --> 00:13:25.370
So well, the
Autobahn gets built.

