whether you are a Barcelone,
or a Catalon, or a Spaniard,

00:28:29.220 --> 00:28:33.080
but it is also a
collapse of community.

00:28:33.080 --> 00:28:35.940
And you can see that in
many parts of the world.

00:28:35.940 --> 00:28:39.910
So let us go to argument one.

00:28:39.910 --> 00:28:43.560
Argument one, the multiple
failures of elites.

00:28:43.560 --> 00:28:52.450
Now if you look at Brussels, a
lot has happened in Brussels.

00:28:52.450 --> 00:28:55.340
The EU has brought trade.

00:28:55.340 --> 00:29:00.000
The EU has brought the Schengen
agreement, which allows

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.350
people to travel in and out.

00:29:01.350 --> 00:29:07.240
It has allowed mobility of
goods, services, and people.

00:29:07.240 --> 00:29:12.390
But it is also a place that
is narrow and technocratic.

00:29:12.390 --> 00:29:15.570
It is far too removed from
the lives of the people.

00:29:15.570 --> 00:29:17.250
It is opaque.

00:29:17.250 --> 00:29:19.100
It is wasteful.

00:29:19.100 --> 00:29:21.340
The EU parliament
in Strasbourg is

00:29:21.340 --> 00:29:25.460
something the parliament just
travels to for a few days,

00:29:25.460 --> 00:29:27.510
for a huge waste.

00:29:27.510 --> 00:29:29.720
And because this
has been written,

00:29:29.720 --> 00:29:33.400
a treaty now-- amending a
treaty is too complicated.

00:29:33.400 --> 00:29:39.370
And the waste and the
disconnect that the EU

00:29:39.370 --> 00:29:41.860
has acquired from the
lives of the people

00:29:41.860 --> 00:29:44.640
is breeding a resentment.

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:51.100
Because at the end of the
day, narrow and technocratic

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:55.350
leadership is not enough.

00:29:55.350 --> 00:29:58.060
There has to be a vision
of where you are headed,

00:29:58.060 --> 00:30:01.560
what you are doing, and
some fundamental delivery

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:06.180
of solutions when a crisis hits.

00:30:06.180 --> 00:30:08.010
And a crisis has hit Europe.

00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:09.900
Europe has multiple problems.

00:30:09.900 --> 00:30:11.870
The Euro is not exactly working.

00:30:11.870 --> 00:30:15.060
There is a debt crisis, partly
because the euro was rushed,

00:30:15.060 --> 00:30:17.765
and countries like
Greece and Italy

00:30:17.765 --> 00:30:23.720
hired Goldman-Sachs-- you
know, did creative accounting.

00:30:23.720 --> 00:30:26.730
And that creative
accounting led them in,

00:30:26.730 --> 00:30:29.245
and then everyone lent
to them, thinking now

00:30:29.245 --> 00:30:31.120
that you had the euro,
everyone was the same,

00:30:31.120 --> 00:30:32.703
everyone was Germany,
and the chickens

00:30:32.703 --> 00:30:34.960
have come home to roost.

00:30:34.960 --> 00:30:38.830
And when the crisis came, the
reaction of European elites

00:30:38.830 --> 00:30:42.720
was of typical
petty bureaucrats.

00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:45.590
And people may not
understand what is wrong,

00:30:45.590 --> 00:30:47.430
but they know
something is wrong.

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:51.650
And they want certain
answers, or some

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:55.290
promises of solutions, which
are somewhat acted upon,

00:30:55.290 --> 00:30:57.440
if not in their entirety.

00:30:57.440 --> 00:30:59.620
Now let's take another
example of immigration.

00:30:59.620 --> 00:31:01.890
Immigration is an issue.

00:31:01.890 --> 00:31:06.540
Yesterday, I was sitting with
a few Germans, all of whom

00:31:06.540 --> 00:31:09.270
are very anti-far
right, but all of whom

00:31:09.270 --> 00:31:10.760
were talking about
how immigrants

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:14.020
have started posing a problem
to safety-- some sections,

00:31:14.020 --> 00:31:15.400
not all.

00:31:15.400 --> 00:31:19.110
And they talked about a
family that their friends

00:31:19.110 --> 00:31:20.170
had sheltered.

00:31:20.170 --> 00:31:23.330
They had come through very
traumatic circumstances.

00:31:23.330 --> 00:31:28.170
And the young kids would go to
school and beat up other kids.

00:31:28.170 --> 00:31:30.796
Because if you come from
traumatic circumstances,

00:31:30.796 --> 00:31:32.670
you are traumatized,
and now suddenly, you're

00:31:32.670 --> 00:31:36.770
with other kids, and you're
socialized in a certain way.

00:31:36.770 --> 00:31:38.010
And that is a problem.

00:31:38.010 --> 00:31:42.490
Immigration, which is too
high, which happens too fast,

00:31:42.490 --> 00:31:45.790
creates social pressures,
particularly if you're

00:31:45.790 --> 00:31:51.520
coming from a conservative
society to a slightly,

00:31:51.520 --> 00:31:56.610
shall we say, open
and hedonistic one.

00:31:56.610 --> 00:32:00.700
For instance, New Year's Eve
in Germany led to mass attacks

00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:01.300
on women.

00:32:01.300 --> 00:32:02.130
Some were raped.

00:32:04.930 --> 00:32:09.510
And the government tried to
push it under the carpet.

00:32:09.510 --> 00:32:11.550
That creates anger.

00:32:11.550 --> 00:32:14.070
The response of the elites,
whether it is security,

00:32:14.070 --> 00:32:17.060
whether it is immigration,
whether it is economics,

00:32:17.060 --> 00:32:22.030
has been very much a bit
like Marie Antoinette, which

00:32:22.030 --> 00:32:24.970
was when the revolution
began, we have no bread,

00:32:24.970 --> 00:32:27.530
and she said, why don't
they eat cakes instead?

00:32:27.530 --> 00:32:29.290
And that riles up people.

00:32:29.290 --> 00:32:30.960
And that's premise one.

00:32:30.960 --> 00:32:33.790
And the failure is
not just in Brussels.

00:32:33.790 --> 00:32:36.200
The failure is in
London, in Paris.

00:32:36.200 --> 00:32:37.620
Look at Hollande.

00:32:37.620 --> 00:32:43.210
Hollande is like a
chubby bank clerk.

00:32:43.210 --> 00:32:47.450
And I don't mean to be
insulting to bank clerks.

00:32:47.450 --> 00:32:49.630
I think they are very
dignified and do a great job.

00:32:49.630 --> 00:32:53.360
I just think that
Hollande as the president

00:32:53.360 --> 00:32:56.930
is expected to exude a
certain sense of direction,

00:32:56.930 --> 00:32:57.480
some vision.

00:32:57.480 --> 00:33:01.830
And Hollande is lost.

00:33:01.830 --> 00:33:04.130
His suit is far too big for him.

00:33:04.130 --> 00:33:06.600
And people resent that failure.

00:33:06.600 --> 00:33:09.930
Come to Washington, DC,
and I am sure all of you

00:33:09.930 --> 00:33:11.520
are well familiar with this.

00:33:11.520 --> 00:33:14.780
You come to
Washington, DC, the way

00:33:14.780 --> 00:33:18.400
the institutions have now
come to a grinding halt--

00:33:18.400 --> 00:33:20.820
forget the partisan politics.

00:33:20.820 --> 00:33:23.270
That is a problem in itself.

00:33:23.270 --> 00:33:26.410
Let's take the example of
congressmen and senators.

00:33:26.410 --> 00:33:29.970
Let's say Joseph was a
senator, or a congressman.

00:33:29.970 --> 00:33:31.380
Let's start with a Congressman.

00:33:31.380 --> 00:33:33.990
If he was in a
swing seat, he would

00:33:33.990 --> 00:33:36.720
be fundraising constantly.

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:43.180
I have friends who are raising
on average $18,0000 to $25,000

00:33:43.180 --> 00:33:46.850
a day for all their term.

00:33:46.850 --> 00:33:50.732
Now, if you are
raising $825,000 a day,

00:33:50.732 --> 00:33:52.190
how many hours in
the day does that

00:33:52.190 --> 00:33:56.430
leave you for
writing legislation?

00:33:56.430 --> 00:33:58.480
Then you wonder why
legislation is so shoddy.

00:33:58.480 --> 00:34:00.140
Well, there's a reason why. .

00:34:00.140 --> 00:34:03.790
How much time does it leave you
for sitting on the committee

00:34:03.790 --> 00:34:07.230
and holding the feet of
the executive to the fire?

00:34:10.400 --> 00:34:10.940
Do the math.

00:34:10.940 --> 00:34:12.886
I mean, you're all engineers.

00:34:12.886 --> 00:34:18.810
The point is that a
lot of the capitals

00:34:18.810 --> 00:34:19.960
are fundamentally broken.

00:34:19.960 --> 00:34:22.500
The institutions haven't
evolved with the times.

00:34:22.500 --> 00:34:24.290
So that's failure one.

00:34:24.290 --> 00:34:25.909
Failure two, inequality.

00:34:25.909 --> 00:34:28.210
I won't belabor this point.

00:34:28.210 --> 00:34:29.560
There are statistics galore.

00:34:29.560 --> 00:34:32.860
I have kept writing about
this issue for a year.

00:34:32.860 --> 00:34:35.000
And these are not my figures.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:37.389
You look at figures
from the White House

00:34:37.389 --> 00:34:38.989
Council of Economic Advisers.

00:34:38.989 --> 00:34:40.610
You look at OECD figures.

00:34:40.610 --> 00:34:43.320
You look at figures from
practically every government,

00:34:43.320 --> 00:34:47.719
and you see that income
inequality, wealth inequality,

00:34:47.719 --> 00:34:51.905
educational inequality--
all of these have gone up,

00:34:51.905 --> 00:34:55.170
and social mobility
has gone down.

00:34:55.170 --> 00:34:57.440
And when you don't
have this feeling

00:34:57.440 --> 00:34:59.220
that there is
opportunity, there is

00:34:59.220 --> 00:35:02.450
anger, particularly
if people have

00:35:02.450 --> 00:35:04.170
come to expect
opportunity, people

00:35:04.170 --> 00:35:08.120
have come to expect a
lifestyle through media, which

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:10.310
is more affluent,
particularly if you have

00:35:10.310 --> 00:35:13.460
an age of consumerism, where
people define themselves

00:35:13.460 --> 00:35:16.150
by what they have and what we
consume, instead of what we do

00:35:16.150 --> 00:35:18.320
and who they are.

00:35:18.320 --> 00:35:24.100
And so, inequality is a major
reason for a lot of anger.

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:26.590
And part of it is
because of technology.

00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:32.970
Part of it is a broader secular
trend of quantitative easing.

00:35:32.970 --> 00:35:34.620
If you print a lot
of money, and it

00:35:34.620 --> 00:35:37.620
doesn't show up in inflation,
then asset prices go up.

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:40.380
So those who own houses
and those who own shares,

00:35:40.380 --> 00:35:41.474
they are wealthier.

00:35:41.474 --> 00:35:42.890
And those who,
don't they can just

00:35:42.890 --> 00:35:49.470
continue cleaning their
rubbish, and giving massages,

00:35:49.470 --> 00:35:51.780
and teaching yoga.

00:35:51.780 --> 00:35:58.390
But that tension that comes
in with the combination

00:35:58.390 --> 00:36:03.800
of increasing
automation, with not just

00:36:03.800 --> 00:36:08.070
let's see physical jobs as
in a car factory, but also

00:36:08.070 --> 00:36:11.820
all increasingly skilled jobs
with artificial intelligence,

00:36:11.820 --> 00:36:13.840
where you don't need
that many people,

00:36:13.840 --> 00:36:15.900
and combine that with
quantitative easing,

00:36:15.900 --> 00:36:20.480
it makes for a grim spectacle,
and people get angry.

00:36:20.480 --> 00:36:23.680
How do they find things to
do to fill their time with?

00:36:23.680 --> 00:36:26.650
And how do they earn
their daily bread?

00:36:26.650 --> 00:36:28.390
Now, the third
thing-- and this, I

00:36:28.390 --> 00:36:30.260
think is fundamental
and often overlooked--

00:36:30.260 --> 00:36:33.810
is this idea of
collective identity.

00:36:33.810 --> 00:36:35.070
Who are we as a people?

00:36:35.070 --> 00:36:36.650
Man is a social animal.

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:38.190
Plato said that a long time ago.

00:36:38.190 --> 00:36:41.130
All the Eastern
philosophers have said it.

00:36:41.130 --> 00:36:45.940
You don't exist as an
island, or man, or woman.

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:53.030
There is a set of weaving,
inextricable, intricate

00:36:53.030 --> 00:36:56.970
relationships that
every individual

00:36:56.970 --> 00:36:59.570
manages to have through life.

00:36:59.570 --> 00:37:05.370
And if you get isolated,
it creates a lot of anger.

00:37:05.370 --> 00:37:12.130
And what has happened is that
communities have sort of broken

00:37:12.130 --> 00:37:13.530
down in the age of consumerism.

00:37:17.760 --> 00:37:23.400
Neighborhoods lack cohesion
in large parts of the world.

00:37:23.400 --> 00:37:29.000
You take the example
of India, where

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:33.640
you have enormous violence
now in the north, where

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:39.570
rape is a real and tangible
concern for any woman going out

00:37:39.570 --> 00:37:42.690
in the evening in the north.

00:37:42.690 --> 00:37:53.160
You take, for instance, this
issue of enormous PTSD amongst

00:37:53.160 --> 00:37:54.880
US demobilized troops.

00:37:57.970 --> 00:38:00.560
In the older times-- not
that things were perfect.

00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:02.310
Things were terrible
in many ways then.

00:38:02.310 --> 00:38:05.050
We had serfdom, and
slavery, and whatnot.

00:38:05.050 --> 00:38:06.800
But in the older
times, often when

00:38:06.800 --> 00:38:08.410
soldiers came back
from war, they

00:38:08.410 --> 00:38:09.590
went back to their village.

00:38:09.590 --> 00:38:12.620
They had a whole community
support structure.

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:16.410
Now when you come back, you're
coming back to a suburb.

00:38:16.410 --> 00:38:18.120
You might end up
having a divorce.

00:38:18.120 --> 00:38:19.330
Your wife may leave you.

00:38:19.330 --> 00:38:22.500
You may end up getting
into a spiral of addiction.

00:38:22.500 --> 00:38:26.790
You may not have that support
structure of the community.

00:38:26.790 --> 00:38:30.560
And that lack of community
support structure,

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:34.770
that lack of autonomy,
self-autonomy,

00:38:34.770 --> 00:38:39.050
leads to not just anger
but also identity.

00:38:39.050 --> 00:38:41.515
And Freud talked
about this a lot.

00:38:41.515 --> 00:38:44.970
He talked about it as
Nazis move on the rise,

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:52.040
and his insight was that there
are destructive forces that

00:38:52.040 --> 00:38:57.490
lurk and emerge, particularly
in times of crisis.

00:38:57.490 --> 00:39:02.210
And during these moments,
when this happens,

00:39:02.210 --> 00:39:07.380
then people look for
certain certitudes in life.

00:39:07.380 --> 00:39:12.280
And that certitude
can be very appealing

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:15.290
if it harks back
to a golden age.

00:39:15.290 --> 00:39:18.850
The Nazis were harking
back to a golden age,

00:39:18.850 --> 00:39:23.070
a pristine age of
the idyllic identity,

00:39:23.070 --> 00:39:25.310
the folk memory of Germany.

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:27.980
If you look at Islamic
State, what does it say?

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:30.310
It says there is
this book, right?

00:39:30.310 --> 00:39:33.410
The Koran.

00:39:33.410 --> 00:39:35.775
This gives you an entire
template of life and afterlife.

00:39:38.900 --> 00:39:41.130
Describes everything.

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:42.166
And this is it.

00:39:44.680 --> 00:39:47.970
This will be your salvation.

00:39:47.970 --> 00:39:56.640
It's a very powerful appeal
if you believe in faith.

00:39:56.640 --> 00:40:01.130
Now, a lot of times when people
believe in religion, it just

00:40:01.130 --> 00:40:05.550
helps them provide an
expression of spirituality.

00:40:05.550 --> 00:40:12.500
It helps them gain a sense
of cultural continuity,

00:40:12.500 --> 00:40:18.900
and it is a fulcrum
of a community.

00:40:18.900 --> 00:40:21.960
But when things become
literal, and fanatical,

00:40:21.960 --> 00:40:23.890
and you have priests
who are telling you

00:40:23.890 --> 00:40:28.060
what these books mean--
whether it is this book, which

00:40:28.060 --> 00:40:30.940
is the Bible, of course,
which a lot of people

00:40:30.940 --> 00:40:32.820
hark back to in this country.

00:40:32.820 --> 00:40:37.480
And they say, check
the Bible, and they

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:41.030
claim that this is the
reason why you shouldn't have

00:40:41.030 --> 00:40:43.170
a right to abortion, or
this is the reason why you

00:40:43.170 --> 00:40:46.220
should support x and oppose y.

00:40:46.220 --> 00:40:50.710
You're getting an absolutist,
fundamentalist point of view

00:40:50.710 --> 00:40:54.030
that harks back to a pristine
golden age, that harks back

00:40:54.030 --> 00:40:56.860
to certitude and truth,
that harks back to clearly

00:40:56.860 --> 00:40:59.850
codified definitions.

00:40:59.850 --> 00:41:03.505
That provides you
a map of everything

00:41:03.505 --> 00:41:07.340
at a time of great
volatility and uncertainty.

00:41:07.340 --> 00:41:10.270
But just before people
jump to the conclusion

00:41:10.270 --> 00:41:15.670
and say all religion
is bad, the flip side

00:41:15.670 --> 00:41:20.880
is that any ideology-- not just
religion, which revolves around

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:25.260
far too much certitude,
whether it is Nazi

00:41:25.260 --> 00:41:27.850
thought as penned by
Adolf Hitler in "Mein

00:41:27.850 --> 00:41:31.300
Kampf," whether it is Stalin,
Joseph Stalin, and his idea

00:41:31.300 --> 00:41:36.280
of fundamentalist
communism, or it is even

00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:38.940
Mustafa Kemal and his
idea of Turkification,

00:41:38.940 --> 00:41:40.530
which was terrible
for the Turks,

00:41:40.530 --> 00:41:43.560
by the way-- sorry,
terrible for the Kurds.

00:41:43.560 --> 00:41:46.720
Any idea that bases
itself on the certitude

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:51.210
of a collective identity that is
ethnic, or religious, or racial

00:41:51.210 --> 00:41:56.080
ends up in a lot
of blood and tears.

00:41:56.080 --> 00:41:58.160
And perhaps that is part
of the human condition,

00:41:58.160 --> 00:42:01.890
because we like to define
ourselves in tribes after all.

00:42:01.890 --> 00:42:06.020
Here at Google, you wear
your tribal signifiers.

00:42:06.020 --> 00:42:08.230
I see Google t-shirts.

00:42:08.230 --> 00:42:14.160
And we want to believe in some
kind of collective mission

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:15.900
and identity.

00:42:15.900 --> 00:42:20.950
And perhaps that is in
many ways wonderful,

00:42:20.950 --> 00:42:24.980
because it allows people
some common identity,

00:42:24.980 --> 00:42:27.980
common purpose,
and common goals.

00:42:27.980 --> 00:42:33.690
But when it's taken to
an unhealthy degree.

00:42:33.690 --> 00:42:39.720
When it is taken to an
irrational belief that

00:42:39.720 --> 00:42:42.840
is beyond questioning,
that is beyond dialogue,

00:42:42.840 --> 00:42:45.650
that is beyond debate,
then the worry begins.

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:48.170
And the point that
I'm making is,

00:42:48.170 --> 00:42:51.600
these forces, these
forces of irrationality,

00:42:51.600 --> 00:42:57.810
these forces of hearkening back
to comfort and infantile sense

00:42:57.810 --> 00:43:00.670
of security-- which,
actually, Eric Fromm talks

00:43:00.670 --> 00:43:03.810
about in "Escape From Freedom."

00:43:03.810 --> 00:43:05.960
Because freedom can
be a terrifying thing.

00:43:05.960 --> 00:43:07.110
It leads to loneliness.

00:43:07.110 --> 00:43:08.230
It leads to isolation.

00:43:08.230 --> 00:43:10.300
It leads to atomization.

00:43:10.300 --> 00:43:12.590
If we are disconnected
from each other,

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:14.300
from one individual
from another,

00:43:14.300 --> 00:43:16.660
or if there are far
too many uncertainties,

00:43:16.660 --> 00:43:20.890
then we want to go back to a
comforting infantile state,

00:43:20.890 --> 00:43:22.590
back to being a child.

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:24.440
But as an adult,
it's not possible.

00:43:24.440 --> 00:43:26.860
And therefore, you
seek this connection

00:43:26.860 --> 00:43:30.270
with a father figure, with an
authoritarian father figure,

00:43:30.270 --> 00:43:33.650
who promises peace and
tranquility, and a happy family

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:36.240
in the Garden of Eden.

00:43:36.240 --> 00:43:38.210
It doesn't quite work that way.

00:43:38.210 --> 00:43:41.780
But this collapse is
particularly important.

